     1	# desktop_app
     2	
     3	## Architecture
     4	- Tauri v2 desktop application with Rust backend and web frontend
     5	- Rust commands are defined in `src-tauri/src/lib.rs` using `#[tauri::command]` macro
     6	- Plugins are registered in the `tauri::Builder` chain in `run()`
     7	- Capabilities (permissions) are configured in `src-tauri/capabilities/default.json`
     8	
     9	## Dependencies
    10	- `tauri-plugin-dialog`: Native file/folder dialogs (`DialogExt`)
    11	- `tauri-plugin-store`: Key-value persistence (`StoreExt`, stored in `app.json`)
    12	- `tauri-plugin-opener`: Default opener plugin
    13	
    14	## Tauri Commands
    15	- Commands use `tauri::AppHandle` for accessing plugins
    16	- Async commands should avoid blocking calls in production; `blocking_pick_folder()` is acceptable for dialog simplicity
    17	- Store plugin path: `"app.json"` stores app-level data like `recent_project`
    18	
    19	## Notes
    20	- `detect_project_config` checks for `.autoresearch/`, `.autoresearch/program.md`, `.autoresearch/agents/`
    21	- `select_project_dir` returns `Option<String>` (None if user cancels)
    22	- The lib name is `desktop_app_lib` (not `desktop_app`) to avoid Windows naming conflict
    23	- `list_issues` calls `gh issue list --json` and also scans `.autoresearch/workflows/issue-*` for processed status
    24	- `check_processed_issues` is a standalone command that only scans processed Issue numbers
    25	- `gh` CLI errors (not installed, no repo, no auth) are surfaced as `Result::Err` strings
    26	- `GhIssue` and `GhLabel` structs use `serde::Deserialize` to parse `gh` JSON output; `createdAt` is renamed via `#[serde(rename)]`
    27	
    28	## Error Handling Patterns
    29	- Tauri commands consistently use `Result<T, String>` for error handling
    30	- All errors are surfaced as descriptive strings via `map_err(|e| format!("...", e))`
    31	- External command errors (gh CLI) are checked via `output.status.success()` before parsing stdout
    32	- File system errors include context about which path failed (e.g., "Failed to read workflows dir")
    33	
    34	## JSON Parsing Patterns
    35	- External command JSON output uses `serde_json::from_str()` with explicit error messages
    36	- Include the raw output in parse error messages for easier debugging
    37	- Use `#[serde(rename = "camelCase")]` for fields that differ from Rust naming conventions
    38	
    39	## Testing Patterns
    40	- When a Tauri command shells out to `gh`, extract pure helper functions for JSON parsing and stderr-to-user-error mapping so unit tests do not depend on a live GitHub CLI session
    41	- For backend command tests, cover both success parsing and representative failure modes (invalid input path, malformed JSON, known `gh` stderr patterns such as missing issues)
